The paper deals with computational geometry problems involving point sets and geometric objects such as rectangles and cuboids. Therefore, cs.CG (Computational Geometry) is the most likely sub-category. The paper also proposes an in-place construction of the k-d tree, which is a classic data structure used in computational geometry, making cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms) another likely sub-category. The paper also involves computer vision (cs.CV) as it deals with recognizing rectangles in a point set. Machine learning (cs.LG) may also be a relevant sub-category as the paper proposes algorithms for finding monochromatic objects of maximum size. Finally, the paper involves optimization problems, which may fall under cs.DM (Discrete Mathematics).
